le paths.\n11. Analyze the capabilities of team members and assign tasks to them based on user Requirements. If the requirements ask to ignore certain tasks, follow the requirements.\n12. If the the user message is a question, use \'reply to human\' to respond to the question, and then end.\n13. Instructions and reply must be in the same language.\n14. Default technology stack is Vite, React, MUI, Tailwind CSS. Web app is the default option when developing software. If use these technology stacks, ask the engineer to delopy the web app after project completion.\n15. You are the only one who decides the programming language for the software, so the instruction must contain the programming language.\n16. Data collection and web/software development are two separate tasks. You must assign these tasks to data analysts and engineers, respectively. Wait for the data collection to be completed before starting the coding.\n\n'}, {'role': 'user', 'content': '[Message] from User to Mike: Write a Python function: \ndef minPath(grid, k):\n    """\n    Given a grid with N rows and N columns (N >= 2) and a positive integer k, \n    each cell of the grid contains a value. Every integer in the range [1, N * N]\n    inclusive appears exactly once on the cells of the grid.\n\n    You have to find the minimum path of length k in the grid. You can start\n    from any cell, and in each step you can move to any of the neighbor cells,\n    in other words, you can go to cells which share an edge with you current\n    cell.\n    Please note that a path of length k means visiting exactly k cells (not\n    necessarily distinct).\n    You CANNOT go off the grid.\n    A path A (of length k) is considered less than a path B (of length k) if\n    after making the ordered lists of the values on the cells that A and B go\n    through (let\'s call them lst_A and lst_B), lst_A is lexicographically less\n    than lst_B, in other words, there exist an integer index i (1 <= i <= k)\n    such that lst_A[i] < lst_B[i] and for any j (1 <= j < i) we have\n    lst_A[j] = lst_B[j].\n    It is guaranteed that the answer is unique.\n    Return an ordered list of the values on the cells that the minimum path go through.\n\n    Examples:\n\n        Input: grid = [ [1,2,3], [4,5,6], [7,8,9]], k = 3\n        Output: [1, 2, 1]\n\n        Input: grid = [ [5,9,3], [4,1,6], [7,8,2]], k = 1\n        Output: [1]\n    """\n \n        IMPORTANT REQUIREMENTS:  \n        1. Save the code to a file named \'minPath.py\'  \n        2. The file must be saved in the project directory: "/Users/user1/CODE/Tester/MetaGPT/humaneval_baseline"  \n        3. The file should contain ONLY the function implementation with proper imports  \n        4. Ensure the file is written to disk before completing the task  \n        \n        '}, {'role': 'assistant', 'content': 'I will create a focused single-task plan for our Engineer, Alex, since this is an XS-sized coding task. I’ll instruct him to implement the Python function minPath(grid, k), ensure it computes the lexicographically minimum path of length k as specified, and save the function-only code to /Users/user1/CODE/Tester/MetaGPT/humaneval_baseline/minPath.py. I’ll include the algorithmic approach, constraints, and file-writing requirements. Then I’ll notify you that Alex has started.\n\n```json\n[\n    {\n        "command_name": "Plan.append_task",\n        "args": {\n            "task_id": "1",\n            "dependent_task_ids": [],\n            "instruction": "Task: Implement and save a Python 3 function per the specification.\\n\\nFunction signature:\\n    def minPath(grid, k):\\n\\nGoal:\\n    Given an N x N grid (N >= 2) containing all unique integers from 1..N*N exactly once, find the lexicographically minimum path of length k (k >= 1). You may start from any cell and move 4-directionally (up, down, left, right) within grid boundaries at each step. A path of length k visits exactly k cells (revisits allowed). Compare paths by the lexicographic order of the sequence of cell values visited. It is guaranteed the answer is unique. Return the ordered list of values along the minimum path.\\n\\nIMPORTANT REQUIREMENTS:\\n  1) Save the code to a file named: minPath.py\\n  2) The file must be saved in the project directory: /Users/user1/CODE/Tester/MetaGPT/humaneval_baseline\\n  3) The file should contain ONLY the function implementation with necessary imports (no tests, prints, main guards, or extra comments beyond minimal docstring if desired)\\n  4) Ensure the file is written to disk before completing the task (create the directory if it does not exist)\\n\\nProgramming language: Python 3\\n\\nSuggested correct algorithm (ensure correctness first):\\n  - Use dynamic programming over path length to achieve lexicographic minimization.\\n  - Let best be an N x N array of sequences for the current step length.\\n  - Initialization (t = 1): best[i][j] = (grid[i][j],)\\n  - For t from 2 to k:\\n      new_best[i][j] = min_lex( best[ni][nj] + (grid[i][j],) ) over all 4-neighbors (ni,nj) of (i,j) within bounds\\n    where min_lex picks lexicographically smallest tuple among candidates.\\n  - Final answer for length k is the lexicographically minimum sequence among all cells at step k.\\n  - If k == 1, simply return the lexicographically minimum singleton among all cells, i.e., the minimal grid value.\\n\\nDetails and constraints:\\n  - Grid values are unique and in [1, N*N].\\n  - Moves must stay within bounds; revisiting is allowed.\\n  - Return a list[int] (convert tuple to list before returning).\\n  - Time complexity: O(k * N^2 * 4 * sequence_compare). Using tuples enables native lexicographic comparison in Python.\\n  - Avoid extra dependencies; no I/O beyond writing the specified file.\\n\\nFile output requirements:\\n  - Path: /Users/user1/CODE/Tester/MetaGPT/humaneval_baseline/minPath.py\\n  - Content: ONLY the function definition (def minPath(grid, k): ...) and any minimal necessary imports (none are strictly required).\\n  - No print statements, no sample runs, no additional code outside the function.\\n\\nExamples for your internal validation (do NOT include test code in the file):\\n  - grid = [[1,2,3],[4,5,6],[7,8,9]], k=3 -> [1,2,1]\\n  - grid = [[5,9,3],[4,1,6],[7,8,2]], k=1 -> [1]\\n",\n            "assignee": "Alex",\n            "task_type": ""\n        }\n    },\n    {\n        "command_name": "TeamLeader.publish_team_message",\n        "args": {\n            "content": "Hi Alex,\\n\\nPlease implement the following Python function and save it to disk exactly as specified.\\n\\nFunction signature:\\n  def minPath(grid, k):\\n\\nSpecification:\\n  - N x N grid (N >= 2) with unique integers 1..N*N. Find the lexicographically minimum path of length k (k >= 1). You may start at any cell; each step moves to a 4-neighbor cell (up/down/left/right) within bounds. A path of length k visits exactly k cells (revisits allowed). Compare by lexicographic order of visited cell values. The answer is unique. Return the ordered list of values along the minimum path.\\n\\nFile and environment requirements:\\n  - Programming language: Python 3\\n  - Save path: /Users/user1/CODE/Tester/MetaGPT/humaneval_baseline/minPath.py\\n  - The file must contain ONLY the function implementation (and any minimal necessary imports). No prints, tests, or extra code.\\n  - Ensure the file is written to disk before marking the task complete. Create the directory if it does not exist.\\n\\nAlgorithmic guidance (ensure correctness):\\n  - DP over path length for lexicographic minimization:\\n    * t=1: best[i][j] = (grid[i][j],)\\n    * For t = 2..k: new_best[i][j] = min_lex( best[ni][nj] + (grid[i][j],) ) over valid neighbors (ni,nj)\\n    * Answer for t=k is min_lex among all new_best[i][j]. For k=1, pick the global minimum singleton.\\n  - Use tuples for native lexicographic comparison; convert to list before returning.\\n  - Complexity: O(k * N^2 * 4).\\n\\nExamples (for your reference only; d